Erratum in
    Int J Radiat Oncol Biol Phys. 2015 Aug 1;92(5):1175. Uyl-de Groot, Cornelia 
A [corrected to Uyl-de Groot, Carin A].

PURPOSE: To evaluate long-term health effects, costs, and cost-effectiveness of 
positron emission tomography (PET)-based isotoxic accelerated radiation therapy 
treatment (PET-ART) compared with conventional fixed-dose CT-based radiation 
therapy treatment (CRT) in non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC).
METHODS AND MATERIALS: Our analysis uses a validated decision model, based on 
data of 200 NSCLC patients with inoperable stage I-IIIB. Clinical outcomes, 
resource use, costs, and utilities were obtained from the Maastro Clinic and the 
literature. Primary model outcomes were the difference in life-years (LYs), 
